<article>
    <h1>Bri&#xAD;tish tel&#xAD;cos face fines if they use &#x2018;high-risk&#x2019; sup&#xAD;pli&#xAD;ers like Huawei</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201125/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-25"><time>2020-11-25</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>LON­DON • Bri­tain’s tele­coms com­pa­nies could be fined up to 10 per cent of turnover or £100,000 (S$179,000) a day if they con­tra­vene a ban on us­ing equip­ment made by China’s Huawei Tech­nolo­gies un­der a new law put for­ward yes­ter­day.</p>
    <p>The Telecom­mu­ni­ca­tions (Se­cu­rity) Bill will boost the se­cu­rity stan­dards of Bri­tish tele­coms net­works and re­move the threat of high-risk ven­dors, the gov­ern­ment said.</p>
    <p>Bri­tain in July de­cided to ban the use of Huawei in 5G net­works from the end of 2027 be­cause of con­cerns that US sanc­tions on chip tech­nol­ogy meant the Chi­nese firm would not be a re­li­able sup­plier.</p>
    <p>The Bill aims to en­shrine that de­ci­sion in law and man­age any risks from other high-risk ven­dors in the fu­ture, with tough penal­ties for tele­cos that break the rules.</p>
    <p>Dig­i­tal Sec­re­tary Oliver Dow­den said the ben­e­fits of 5G and fi­bre net­works could be re­alised only if they were se­cure and re­silient. “This ground­break­ing Bill will give the UK one of the tough­est tele­coms se­cu­rity regimes in the world and al­low us to take the ac­tion nec­es­sary to pro­tect our net­works,” he said.</p>
    <p>Huawei said it was dis­ap­pointed that the Bri­tish gov­ern­ment was look­ing to ex­clude it from the roll-out of 5G.</p>
    <p>“This de­ci­sion is po­lit­i­cally mo­ti­vated and not based on a fair eval­u­a­tion of the risks,” said Huawei vice-pres­i­dent Vic­tor Zhang.</p>
    <p>“It does not serve any­one’s best in­ter­ests as it would move Bri­tain into the dig­i­tal slow lane and put at risk the gov­ern­ment’s lev­el­ling-up agenda.”</p>
    <p>The gov­ern­ment said the tougher se­cu­rity stan­dards in the Bill would also help pro­tect Bri­tain from po­ten­tial cy­ber at­tacks from coun­tries and crim­i­nals.</p>
    <p>Reg­u­la­tor Of­com will be given the duty of mon­i­tor­ing and as­sess­ing the se­cu­rity of tele­coms providers.</p>


</article>

